ðŸŽ¯ Interview Explanation (1â€“2 lines)

â€œI loop once through the string, ignore non-alphabets, and use indexOf() on a fixed vowel string to classify vowels and consonants.â€ 




public class CountCharacters {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "Hello World 123!";
        int vowels = 0, consonants = 0, digits = 0;

        // Convert to lowercase to simplify comparisons
        str = str.toLowerCase();

        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            char ch = str.charAt(i);

            if (ch == 'a' || ch == 'e' || ch == 'i' || ch == 'o' || ch == 'u') {
                vowels++;
            } else if (Character.isLetter(ch)) {
                // If it's a letter but not a vowel, it's a consonant
                consonants++;
            } else if (Character.isDigit(ch)) {
                digits++;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Vowels: " + vowels);
        System.out.println("Consonants: " + consonants);
        System.out.println("Digits: " + digits);
    }
}
      TC: 
, where 
 is the length of the string. The program performs a single pass through the string to examine each character.
SC: 
, as the algorithm only uses a few integer variables (vowels, consonants, digits) to store counts. This does not grow with the size of the input string.
